{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "UniformGrid",
        "description": "Uniform vertical grid discretization for roof and wall columns in the urban canopy thermal solver. Computes node depths at layer midpoints (Oleson Eq. 4.5), layer thicknesses (Eq. 4.6), and interface depths (Eq. 4.7) for a column of total thickness `dz_total` divided into N equal-thickness layers. Used for roofs and walls (homogeneous opaque material — concrete, brick, etc.); the road column uses the exponential grid (sibling `exponential_grid.esm`) because it overlies real soil where near-surface diurnal cycles dominate. Migrated from UrbanCanopy.jl@9200edd4 src/roof_wall_road_snow_temperatures.jl:830 (`UniformGrid` @component). Implements Oleson et al. (2010, CLM Tech Note Ch. 4 §4.1, Eqs. 4.5-4.7). Parameterized as observed-only: `dz_total` is the only input parameter; z_node_i, dz_layer_i, z_interface_j are algebraic outputs. Upstream `N` (number of layers) is fixed to its canonical default 15 for serialization (per-N templating lives outside the ESM scalar schema and is not needed for the urban-canopy use case).",
        "tags": [
            "urban_canopy",
            "temperatures",
            "grid",
            "discretization",
            "observed-only",
            "clmu"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-12T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "UrbanCanopy.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-0254)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Oleson, K. W., et al. (2010). Technical Description of version 4.0 of the Community Land Model (CLM). NCAR Technical Note NCAR/TN-478+STR. Chapter 4, Section 4.1, Eqs. 4.5-4.7, p. 91."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "UniformGrid": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: UrbanCanopy.jl@9200edd4f15609f20339d3a7d104de8064544310:src/roof_wall_road_snow_temperatures.jl:830\nUpstream `UniformGrid` is an MTK `@component` parameterized by N (default 15) declaring one `@parameters` (`Δz_total`, total column thickness in m) and three arrays of `@variables`: z_node(t)[1:N], Δz_layer(t)[1:N], z_interface(t)[1:N+1] (with N+1 entries where index j maps to paper i=j-1). Unlike the sibling `ExponentialGrid` (which uses a `@constants` block to fix the scaling factor `f_s = 0.025` m), the UniformGrid takes the column thickness as a hand-set parameter — canonical caller is the roof/wall PDESystem at roof_wall_road_snow_temperatures.jl:1112 which passes `Δz_total = 0.3` m.\n\nFor ESM serialization N is fixed to the canonical upstream default of 15; the .esm encodes the full unfolded scalar system: 15 z_node states, 15 dz_layer states, 16 z_interface states (46 algebraic equations total). This matches the unfold-to-scalar convention adopted by the other urban-canopy temps migrations in this rig (e.g. exponential_grid.esm, snow_melt_no_layers.esm, total_phase_change_energy.esm). The upstream Julia tests (roof_wall_road_snow_temperatures_test.jl:912-972) exercise multiple N values (3, 5, 15); the inner-layer formulas are identical for any N (only dz_layer_15 and z_interface_16 depend explicitly on N), so the assertion values pinned here at N=15, dz_total=0.3 m are also exact for any larger N choice with the dz/N spacing rescaled — i.e. moving to a templated representation in the future will not invalidate the per-layer reference values, only extend them.\n\nUnicode `Δ` in `Δz_total` and `Δz_layer` is renamed `dz_total` and `dz_layer` for ASCII identifier names per the urban-canopy convention (matches snow_density.esm renaming `ρ` → `rho` and exponential_grid.esm renaming `Δz_layer` → `dz_layer`); the ESM identifier-pattern allows unicode but the rig-wide ASCII convention keeps editor and tooling support uniform.\n\nObservability classification: this component is functionally observed-only — every output state is given by a single algebraic equation in terms of the parameter dz_total and other state outputs (the `(t)` time index has no role since there is no derivative anywhere). Test scenarios use `time_span: [0, 1]` and sample at t=0 to mirror the convention used by sibling observed-only files (exponential_grid.esm, snow_melt_no_layers.esm, total_phase_change_energy.esm, snow_density.esm).\n\nDefault parameter rationale: `dz_total = 0.3` m matches the upstream canonical caller (`RoofTemperaturePDE` at roof_wall_road_snow_temperatures.jl:1112) which is the only consumer of UniformGrid in the upstream model. With N=15 this yields a uniform 2 cm layer thickness — appropriate for capturing diurnal-scale heat conduction through opaque urban materials. Upstream Julia has no default in the `@parameters` block; the canonical value is supplied by the caller.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-9): observed-only algebraic system (no ODE integration); the only non-trivial roundoff path is the chain `(i - 0.5) * (dz_total / N)` → linear combinations — IEEE-754 ULP precision throughout. 1e-9 leaves comfortable headroom above ULP roundoff and matches the convention used by sibling observed-only files in this rig (exponential_grid.esm, total_phase_change_energy.esm, etc.). The pinned `dz_layer_i` reference values include ULP-level deviations from the algebraic value 0.02 m (e.g. `dz_layer_3 = 0.020000000000000004`, `dz_layer_15 = 0.019999999999999962`) reflecting the order-of-evaluation in the upstream IEEE-754 expression; the rel=1e-9 tolerance accommodates these without requiring a relaxed tolerance per assertion. Tighter `abs: 1.0e-12` is asserted on z_interface_1 = 0 (exactly zero by construction) so the assertion does not silently accept a stuck-at-1e-3 regression."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-09
            },
            "variables": {
                "dz_total": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 0.3,
                    "description": "Total thickness of the roof or wall column (Oleson et al. 2010 Table 1.3). Canonical value 0.3 m matches the upstream RoofTemperaturePDE caller."
                },
                "z_node_1": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m",
                    "description": "Node depth of layer 1 (Oleson Eq. 4.5): z_1 = (1 - 0.5) * (dz_total / 15)"
                },
                "z_node_2": {
                    "type": "state",
